UN announces new objectives in the fight against poverty
The United Nations will begin immediately to develop a series of new objectives with which the 12 years ago proclaimed Millennium Development Goals to combat poverty should be replaced.
In the run-up to the summit on sustainable development in Rio de Janeiro, Australian diplomats played a key role in the push for "sustainable development goals" to replace the Millennium Development Goals expire in 2015.
They were in the final draft of the document by world leaders, including Ms Gillard, will be adopted at the summit.
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon said on the evening of the summit, the time has come, "on the national interests of matters."
"I am pleased that the Member States have agreed a process, with the universal sustainable development goals are to be agreed upon," he said.
"These goals are on our progress in the Millennium Development Goals and an integral part of the framework for the development after 2015.
I shall spare no effort, the mandate given to me by the Member States, in order to implement our vision of sustainable development goals, to build on the success of the Millennium Development Goals. "
